revision.text:
{{refimprove|date=December 2011}} {{italictitle}} '''''Chase's Calendar of Events''''' is an annual American publication, started in 1957 by brothers William (Bill) D. Chase (a [[journalist]] and [[publisher]] from [[Michigan]]), and Harrison V. Chase (a university [[social scientist]] from [[Florida]]).<ref name="nyt-2007">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/30/dining/30holi.html | title = Having a Snack? Make It a Holiday | first = Kim | last = Severson| authorlink = Kim Severson | date = May 30, 2007 | work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name="Miller-2012">{{cite web | url = http://www.annarbor.com/news/chasing-down-days-ann-arbor-founder-of-chases-calendar-of-events-turns-90/ | title = Ann Arbor man, 90, founded catalogue of events for every day of the year | date = April 2, 2012 | first = Janet | last = Miller | work = [[AnnArbor.com]]}}</ref> It includes special events, holidays, federal and state observances, historic anniversaries, and more unusual celebratory traditions.<ref name=McGraw/> Bill Chase worked as a newspaper librarian and saw a need for "a single reference source for calendar dates, and for authoritative and current information about various observances throughout the year".<ref name=McGraw>[http://mhprofessional.com/?page=/mhp/categories/chases/content/about_chases.html McGraw Hill] profile</ref>
The brothers gathered information on events and the first edition of 2,000 copies was printed for 1958. "It was 32 pages, contained 364 entries and sold for $1", while recent editions are 752 pages and contain more than 12,000 entries.<ref name=McGraw/> A promotion sponsored by the US Chamber of Commerce was added in 1958: a pamphlet listed commercial promotions as Special Days, Weeks and Months, and remained in future editions.<ref name=McGraw/> Contemporary Books in Chicago, Illinois, took over publication in 1983 and the Chases retired in 1987 from compiling the calendar, which is now handled by an in-house staff of editors and researchers. Contemporary Books was acquired by [[Tribune Media|Tribune]] in 1993 and sold to [[McGraw-Hill Companies]] in September 2000. <ref>{{Cite web| title = Tribune acquisitions: Tribune Co. said Tuesday it reached...| work = tribunedigital-chicagotribune| accessdate = 2016-08-02| url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-07-06/news/9307070173_1_contemporary-books-tribune-distribution-of-interactive-multimedia}}</ref><ref name=McGraw/> McGraw-Hill sold the property to [[Rowman and Littlefield|Rowman and Littlefield Publishing Group]] in January 2015, where it is now published by Bernan Press, an imprint of RLPG. <ref>Rowman and Littlefield press release, Jan 28, 2015</ref> ==Sections== Sections of the calendar include * Astronomical Phenomena * Religious Observances * National and International Observances and Civic Holidays * Special Days, Weeks and Months * Presidential Proclamations * Events and Festivals * Anniversaries * Birthdays Today <ref name=McGraw/>
